rComments: The most intellectually stimulating professor I even had. His lectures may be well organized. He may not explain everything in that much detail. But this is a doctorate-level course. Abilities in Independent study is expected. Most importantly, I learned more from his class than from any other classes. He changed my way of thinking.

Lectures and notes are fairly straightforward, but not particularly detailed or well-paced. Lack of support through problem sets, exercises, or a textbook is really frustrating. Doing well in the course seems to require a lot of self-directed learning, and not in a good way.

This prof is the worst lecturer I've had in my 2 years at U of T. He promised to post practice problems for us to study before the test and he has yet to post them online. (test this week). His lecture is seriously a torture.. He's really unclear and his writing is so bad that 100% of the time we are trying to decrypt what he writes.

His lectures are rather boring, just an abridged retelling of the textbook pages. The classes are useless, you have to do everything by yourself. No thoughtful comments on the topics covered. Very bad and unfair grading. Would not recommend him.

Seemed like a good prof at first, good midterm, fair but hard assignments, clear lectureing, but seemed like he developed a genuine hatred for all the students in his course for the final. Introduced completely new material and questions on the final, too many A students failed, they curved up. This wasnt the first time for that either.
was a good prof and avg course until the exam, which was completely new material to us (everyone agreed) i had A's throught and a failed the exam
